## Ordinal Relationships

Vector datasets use ordinal indices to relate data across files. An ordinal is a 0-based position that identifies one record across all files sharing that ordinal space.

### Base vector ordinals

- Range: `0..1950` (1.9K vectors)
- Shared by: `base_vectors[i]`, `metadata_content[i]` — same ordinal, same vector
- `base_vectors[42]` is the 43rd vector; `metadata_content[42]` is its label

### Query ordinals

- Range: `0..50` (50 queries)
- Shared by: `query_vectors[q]`, `metadata_predicates[q]`, `neighbor_indices[q]`, `filtered_neighbor_indices[q]`
- All files indexed by the same `q` describe the same query

### Worked example: query ordinal 42

```
query_vectors[42]              → the 128-dim f32 search vector
neighbor_indices[42]           → i32[10] nearest base ordinals (G facet)
metadata_predicates[42]        → the filter condition for this query (P facet)
metadata_results[42]           → variable-length list of matching base ordinals (R facet)
filtered_neighbor_indices[42]  → i32[10] nearest among matching bases (F facet)
```

The values inside `neighbor_indices[42]` are **base ordinals** (range `0..1950`), not query ordinals. They reference positions in `base_vectors`.

### Ground truth (G facet)

- `neighbor_indices[q]` → `i32[10]` — the 10 nearest base ordinals to query `q`
- 50 queries x 10 neighbors = 500 ordinal pairs
- Sorted by ascending distance (nearest first)

### Predicate evaluation chain

```
metadata_predicates[q]    "field_0 == 5"     (one predicate per query)
        │
        ▼  evaluate against metadata_content[0..N]
metadata_results[q]       [12, 45, 89, ...]  (variable-length: all matching base ordinals)
        │
        ▼  brute-force KNN restricted to matching ordinals
filtered_neighbor_indices[q]  [89, 12, 45, ...]  (top-k nearest among matches)
```

Note: `metadata_results` uses ivvec format (variable-length records) because the number of matching base vectors varies per query. `filtered_neighbor_indices` is fixed-length ivec (always k neighbors).

